    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Getters and Setters"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Getters and setters (accessor properties) let a class expose a field-like API while running code on read or write. From the caller's perspective they look like a plain property; internally they can validate input, compute a derived value, trigger side effects, or delegate to a backing field."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "typescript"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "class Temperature {\n  private _celsius: number;\n\n  constructor(celsius: number) { this._celsius = celsius; }\n\n  get celsius(): number { return this._celsius; }\n  set celsius(value: number) {\n    if (value < -273.15) throw new RangeError('Below absolute zero');\n    this._celsius = value;\n  }\n\n  get fahrenheit(): number { return this._celsius * 9 / 5 + 32; }\n  // No setter \u2014 fahrenheit is read-only from outside\n}\n\nconst t = new Temperature(100);\nconsole.log(t.fahrenheit); // 212  \u2014 no () needed\nt.celsius = 0;             // triggers setter\n// t.celsius = -300;       // throws at runtime\n// t.fahrenheit = 32;      // Error: no setter defined\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Getter/setter pair: private backing field _name, get name() returns it, set name(v) validates before assigning",
          "title": null
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Getter-Only (Computed) Properties"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A getter with no corresponding setter creates a read-only, computed accessor. TypeScript infers the return type automatically. This is preferable to a method call when the value feels like a property \u2014 no parentheses needed at the call site."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "typescript"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "class Circle {\n  constructor(readonly radius: number) {}\n\n  // Computed: no backing field, calculated on demand\n  get diameter(): number { return this.radius * 2; }\n  get area(): number { return Math.PI * this.radius ** 2; }\n  get circumference(): number { return 2 * Math.PI * this.radius; }\n}\n\nconst c = new Circle(5);\nconsole.log(c.diameter);      // 10\nconsole.log(c.area.toFixed(2)); // 78.54\n// c.diameter = 20;           // Error: no setter\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Setter Validation Pattern"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Setters are ideal for input validation \u2014 they enforce invariants at the point of assignment rather than at method call sites. The backing field (prefixed with "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "_",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " by convention) stores the validated state."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "typescript"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "class Email {\n  private _address = '';\n\n  get address(): string { return this._address; }\n\n  set address(value: string) {\n    const trimmed = value.trim().toLowerCase();\n    if (!trimmed.includes('@')) {\n      throw new TypeError(\\`Invalid email: \\${value}\\`);\n    }\n    this._address = trimmed;\n  }\n}\n\nconst e = new Email();\ne.address = '  Alice@Example.COM  '; // normalised silently\nconsole.log(e.address); // 'alice@example.com'\n// e.address = 'not-an-email'; // TypeError\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Getters vs Methods"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Both compute values on demand \u2014 the key difference is the call-site syntax and implied semantics:"
          }
        ]
      },
