          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Use a getter when the result feels like reading a property (isValid, fullName, count). Use a method when it takes arguments, has side effects, or is expensive to compute repeatedly."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Angular Patterns with Getters"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Computed Template Values"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Component getters replace repetitive template expressions and keep the template readable. They are called on every change detection cycle, so they must be cheap (no loops over large arrays, no HTTP calls)."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "typescript"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "@Component({\n  template: \\`\n    <p>{{ fullName }}</p>\n    <button [disabled]=\"!isFormValid\">Submit</button>\n    <span class=\"badge\" [class.urgent]=\"isUrgent\">{{ badgeText }}</span>\n  \\`\n})\nexport class ProfileComponent {\n  firstName = '';\n  lastName  = '';\n  age = 0;\n  priority = 0;\n\n  get fullName(): string { return \\`\\${this.firstName} \\${this.lastName}\\`.trim(); }\n  get isFormValid(): boolean { return !!this.firstName && !!this.lastName; }\n  get isUrgent(): boolean { return this.priority > 7; }\n  get badgeText(): string { return this.isUrgent ? 'Urgent' : 'Normal'; }\n}\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "@Input with a Setter \u2014 Transform on Assignment"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Using a setter for "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "@Input()",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " properties allows you to coerce or validate the value whenever the parent binding changes. This replaces "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "ngOnChanges",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " for simple single-input transformations."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "typescript"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "@Component({ selector: 'app-stars', template: '...' })\nexport class StarsComponent {\n  private _rating = 0;\n  stars: number[] = [];\n\n  @Input()\n  set rating(value: number) {\n    // Clamp to [0, 5] and compute star array\n    this._rating = Math.min(5, Math.max(0, Math.round(value)));\n    this.stars = Array.from({ length: this._rating }, (_, i) => i + 1);\n  }\n\n  get rating(): number { return this._rating; }\n}\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Getter + Signal Combination"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In signal-based components, a getter can read from one or more signals to produce a derived value without creating a computed signal explicitly \u2014 useful for simple, one-off expressions."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "typescript"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "@Component({ template: '<p>{{ label }}</p>' })\nexport class CounterComponent {\n  count = signal(0);\n\n  get label(): string {\n    // Reads signal in template context \u2014 re-evaluates on signal change\n    return this.count() === 1 ? '1 item' : \\`\\${this.count()} items\\`;\n  }\n\n  increment(): void { this.count.update(n => n + 1); }\n}\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pitfalls"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Getters that Trigger Change Detection Loops"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A getter that returns a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "new object or array instance",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " on every call will cause infinite change detection in Angular's default strategy, because the reference always changes."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "typescript"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// BAD \u2014 new array on every call \u2192 endless CD loop\nget activeItems(): Item[] {\n  return this.items.filter(i => i.active); // new array each call\n}\n\n// GOOD \u2014 cache with a computed signal or compute once in a field\nreadonly activeItems = computed(() => this.items().filter(i => i.active));\n\n// ALSO GOOD \u2014 if items is a plain array, filter in an OnPush component\n// and update via immutable replacement\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Forgetting the return type on a Getter"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "TypeScript infers getter return types, but in large codebases explicit return types make intent clear and catch type drift when the backing field changes."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "typescript"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "class Store {\n  private _items: string[] = [];\n\n  // Inferred as string[] \u2014 OK, but explicit is safer in teams\n  get items(): readonly string[] { return this._items; }\n\n  // Without explicit return type \u2014 if _items becomes number[], TS catches it here\n}\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Lazy Initialisation with Getters"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A getter can defer expensive computation until the value is first accessed, then cache the result. This pattern (memoisation) avoids computing a value that may never be needed."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "typescript"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "class Document {\n  private _wordCount: number | null = null;\n\n  constructor(readonly text: string) {}\n\n  // Computed on first access, cached afterwards\n  get wordCount(): number {\n    if (this._wordCount === null) {\n      this._wordCount = this.text.split(/\\s+/).filter(Boolean).length;\n    }\n    return this._wordCount;\n  }\n}\n\nconst doc = new Document('Hello world TypeScript is great');\nconsole.log(doc.wordCount); // 5 \u2014 computed now\nconsole.log(doc.wordCount); // 5 \u2014 returned from cache\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Abstract Getters and Setters"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Getters and setters can be abstract, forcing subclasses to implement them. This is useful when the abstract class defines a template method that reads from an accessor, but the storage strategy varies per subclass."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "typescript"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "abstract class StorageAdapter {\n  // Subclass decides HOW the key is stored\n  abstract get storageKey(): string;\n  abstract get(key: string): string | null;\n  abstract set(key: string, value: string): void;\n\n  // Template methods use the abstract accessor\n  saveJson(data: object): void {\n    this.set(this.storageKey, JSON.stringify(data));\n  }\n\n  loadJson<T>(): T | null {\n    const raw = this.get(this.storageKey);\n    return raw ? JSON.parse(raw) as T : null;\n  }\n}\n\nclass LocalStorageAdapter extends StorageAdapter {\n  get storageKey(): string { return 'app-data'; }\n  get(key: string): string | null { return localStorage.getItem(key); }\n  set(key: string, value: string): void { localStorage.setItem(key, value); }\n}\n\nclass InMemoryAdapter extends StorageAdapter {\n  private store: Record<string, string> = {};\n  get storageKey(): string { return '__mem__'; }\n  get(key: string): string | null { return this.store[key] ?? null; }\n  set(key: string, value: string): void { this.store[key] = value; }\n}\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Setters in Angular Reactive Forms"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Reactive form controls emit new values through "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "valueChanges",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " observables, but sometimes you want to expose a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "@Input()",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " setter that syncs the control with an incoming value from the parent without the parent knowing the internal form structure."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "typescript"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "@Component({\n  selector: 'app-quantity-input',\n  template: \\`\n    <input type=\"number\" [formControl]=\"ctrl\">\n    <span>{{ errorMessage }}</span>\n  \\`\n})\nexport class QuantityInputComponent {\n  ctrl = new FormControl(0, [Validators.required, Validators.min(1)]);\n\n  @Input()\n  set value(v: number) {\n    // Sync parent value into form control without emitting valueChanges\n    this.ctrl.setValue(v, { emitEvent: false });\n  }\n\n  get value(): number { return this.ctrl.value ?? 0; }\n\n  get errorMessage(): string {\n    if (this.ctrl.errors?.['min']) return 'Must be at least 1';\n    if (this.ctrl.errors?.['required']) return 'Required';\n    return '';\n  }\n}\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Getters in Angular Services \u2014 Derived State"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Services often hold raw state in signals and expose derived getters for convenience. This keeps the signal store minimal while providing rich read API."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "typescript"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "interface AuthState {\n  user: User | null;\n  token: string | null;\n  expiresAt: number | null;\n}\n\n@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })\nexport class AuthService {\n  private readonly _state = signal<AuthState>({ user: null, token: null, expiresAt: null });\n\n  // Public computed properties via getters \u2014 no separate signal/computed needed\n  get isAuthenticated(): boolean {\n    const s = this._state();\n    return !!s.token && (s.expiresAt ?? 0) > Date.now();\n  }\n\n  get currentUser(): User | null { return this._state().user; }\n  get userName(): string { return this._state().user?.displayName ?? 'Guest'; }\n  get hasExpired(): boolean {\n    const exp = this._state().expiresAt;\n    return exp !== null && exp < Date.now();\n  }\n\n  login(user: User, token: string, expiresAt: number): void {\n    this._state.set({ user, token, expiresAt });\n  }\n\n  logout(): void {\n    this._state.set({ user: null, token: null, expiresAt: null });\n  }\n}\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Getters reading from signals are evaluated on every call \u2014 Angular's template change detection will call them frequently. For expensive derivations, use computed() instead to memoize."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Testing Getters and Setters"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Getters and setters are tested like any other class member \u2014 call the setter and assert the getter, or vice versa:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "typescript"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "describe('Temperature', () => {\n  it('converts celsius to fahrenheit via getter', () => {\n    const t = new Temperature(100);\n    expect(t.fahrenheit).toBe(212);\n  });\n\n  it('clamps input through setter', () => {\n    const t = new Temperature(0);\n    expect(() => { t.celsius = -300; }).toThrow(RangeError);\n  });\n\n  it('normalises email address on assignment', () => {\n    const e = new Email();\n    e.address = '  Alice@EXAMPLE.COM  ';\n    expect(e.address).toBe('alice@example.com');\n  });\n});\n\n// Angular @Input setter test \u2014 trigger via TestBed or direct\ndescribe('StarsComponent @Input setter', () => {\n  it('clamps rating to [0, 5]', () => {\n    const fixture = TestBed.createComponent(StarsComponent);\n    const comp = fixture.componentInstance;\n    comp.rating = 10;\n    expect(comp.rating).toBe(5);\n    expect(comp.stars.length).toBe(5);\n  });\n});\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Summary"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "get name()",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " \u2014 accessor read without () at call site; ideal for computed, property-like values."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "set name(v)",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " \u2014 intercept assignment; validate, transform, or trigger side effects."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  "A getter without a setter is effectively read-only from the outside."
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  "Backing fields (private _x) hold the actual state; accessors control access to them."
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  "In Angular: use getters for cheap computed template values, use @Input setters to transform values on change, and avoid getters that allocate new objects (triggers CD loops)."
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}